s for an American audience. This book investigates the meanings attached to the work as it circulated through Europe during the early Cold War in a kind of symbolic musical remigration, focusing on six case studies: West Germany, Austria, Norway, East Germany, Poland, and Czechoslovakia. Each case is unique, informed by individual geopolitical concerns, but this analysis also reveals common themes in anxieties about musical modernism, Holocaust memory and culpability, the coexistence of Jews and former Nazis, anti-Semitism, dislocation, and the presence of occupying forces on both sides of the Cold War divide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a20th century world history.  aa survivor in warsaw.  aanti semitism.  aarnold schoenberg.  aaustria.  aaustrian composer.  acantata.  achromatic scale.  acold war.  acomposer.  acultural history.  aczechoslovakia.  adeath camps.  adeath.  adegenerate music.  adodecaphony.  aeast germany.  ageopolitical concerns.  ageopolitics.  aholocaust victims.  aholocaust.  ajewish composer.  alens of performance.  amass death.  amemory.  amusic.  amusical modernism.  anazi.  anorway.  apoland.  apostwar europe.  areception studies.  asecond world war.  atwelve tone technique.  awest germany.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095770140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520957701/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY